{
  "id": "q-smart-wallet-fee-sponsorship",
  "question": "How can a Stellar smart-wallet user receive and use USDC without first holding XLM for transaction fees and account reserves?",
  "surface": [
    "skills.stellar-dev.agentic-payments",
    "skills.stellar-dev.dapp",
    "stellarDocs.search_wallet_dapp_docs"
  ],
  "golden": {
    "answer": "Start with the account type. A C-address can hold USDC through its Stellar Asset Contract interface/balance without a G-account or trustline reserve; a G-account still has activation and trustline reserves unless those entries are sponsored. A fee bump or relayer pays transaction fees, while beginSponsoringFutureReserves/endSponsoringFutureReserves assigns eligible reserve liability. Deployment and resources still cost someone. Token-paid FeeForwarder designs and hosted facilitators are current provider designs with caps, liquidity, and abuse controls, not a universal native paymaster.",
    "keyFacts": [
      "A C-address SAC balance needs no G-account or trustline reserve; a G-account retains activation and trustline reserves unless sponsored.",
      "A fee bump or relayer pays transaction fees, while beginSponsoringFutureReserves/endSponsoringFutureReserves assigns reserve liability.",
      "USDC is used through its Stellar Asset Contract interface/balance, not as a separate wrapped asset.",
      "Token-paid relaying and hosted facilitators are provider designs with caps, liquidity, and abuse controls, not a universal native paymaster."
    ],
    "avoid": [
      "Gasless onboarding eliminates all network and reserve costs rather than shifting them to a sponsor.",
      "A classic account can hold an issued USDC asset without a trustline or sponsored trustline."
    ],
    "notes": "Status-sensitive details are stated as of 2026-07-11; grade later sourced changes leniently and require dated primary evidence."
  },
